405. J Neurol Sci. 1987 Nov;81(2-3):155-8. doi: 10.1016/0022-510x(87)90092-x.

Life spans of Duchenne muscular dystrophy patients in the hospital care program 
in Japan.

Mukoyama M(1), Kondo K, Hizawa K, Nishitani H.

Author information:
(1)National Institute of Neuroscience, NCPN, Tokyo, Japan.

Analysis of 176 autopsy cases of Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) demonstrated 
that (1) hospitalized patients showed longer life spans than their 
non-hospitalized affected maternal uncles, (2) patients hospitalized recently 
lived longer than those hospitalized in the past, and (3) pulmonary infection 
has become a less frequent cause of death in recent years, whereas dystrophic 
changes of the cardiac and respiratory muscles are more closely related with 
recent fatal cases. These results indicate the changing life span expectancy of 
patients with DMD and the changes in cause of death over the last decade, 
probably owing to the benefits of a hospital care program.

