422. Clin Reprod Fertil. 1986 Feb;4(1):55-64.

Fertility, infertility and generation replacement.

Borrie WD.

Throughout most of human history 'natural fertility' and life expectations of 
about 35 years kept population numbers reasonably balanced; but the achievement 
of life expectations of 75 or more years destroyed this 'natural' system. As 
longevity increased amongst Western peoples, explosive growth rates were only 
prevented by increasingly efficient checks on fertility. Today, these checks are 
so universal and so efficient in Australia and in many other Western countries 
that 'intrinsic' levels of fertility are below generation replacement level. 
Changes in fecundity were not a significant factor in this demographic 
revolution; at least 10-12% of couples remain without issue, but the prime cause 
of the change is the evolution of the two-child family, a process which now 
involves only about a sixth of a couple's fecund married life. For the rest of 
their years most couples are now voluntarily infertile. Correction of 
involuntary sterility is important to individual couples but has little 
significance in terms of generation replacement.

PIP: Increasing longevity in Western countries has required efficient checks on 
natural fertility to avert explosive population growth rates. In Australia 
today, intrinsic levels of fertility are below generation replacement level as a 
result of voluntary infertility. In recent years, total fertility has averaged 
only 1.9 births, although the effects of the baby boom years of the 1950s and 
1960s will continue to yield a positive natural growth until about the year 
2010. At least 10-12% of couples remain childless, but the major cause of the 
trend toward below replacement level fertility has been the evolution of the 
2-child family. Most couples are now voluntarily infertile for 5/6 of fecund 
married life. More efficient methods of fertility control, in particular 
sterilization, and the prevalence of abortion have enabled women to postpone 
their 1st birth and limit family size. Correction of involuntary sterility is of 
importance to individual couples, but has little significance in terms of 
generation replacement.

PMID: 3708509 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


