Mortality and facial dyskinesia.

McClelland HA, Dutta D, Metcalfe A, Kerr TA.

In 1965 a psychiatric in-patient population was surveyed for the prevalence of 
facial dyskinesia. The present investigation reports on their survival time. 
Among male and female patients with functional disorders (mostly schizophrenia) 
there was a strong association between moderate or severe facial dyskinesia and 
shortened survival, but no clinical factors were found to explain this. Mild 
facial dyskinesia in functional disorders was not associated with reduced life 
expectancy and may be attributable to the general effects of ageing rather than 
to a specific pathological process. Among patients with primary organic brain 
syndromes, dyskinesia was not associated with reduced life expectancy.

