Prechtl HF.

A new hypothesis is presented concerning the maturation of the human nervous 
system and the duration of pregnancy. It has been found that many neural 
functions characteristic of the fetus continue after birth until a major 
transformation takes place at the end of the second postnatal month. From a 
comparative perspective the duration of pregnancy in man is relatively short 
among primates. An explanation may be found in metabolic constraint. The special 
energy demands of a large fetal nervous system and the build-up of a 
subcutaneous fat deposit may have prevented a proportional prolongation of 
pregnancy during evolution of hominids.

